        <title type="html"><![CDATA[BuckleScript 1.7.0]]></title>
        <id>https://bucklescript.github.io/blog/2017/10/07/release-1-7-0.html</id>
        <link href="https://bucklescript.github.io/blog/2017/10/07/release-1-7-0.html">
        </link>
        <updated>2017-10-07T06:00:00Z</updated>
        <summary type="html"><![CDATA[<h4><a class="anchor" aria-hidden="true" id="first-class-uncurried-calling-convention"></a><a href="#first-class-uncurried-calling-convention" aria-hidden="true" class="hash-link"><svg class="hash-link-icon" aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>First class uncurried calling convention</h4>
<p>As a functional language, the vanilla OCaml only provides curried calling convention,
BuckleScript employs fairly <a href="http://bucklescript.github.io/bucklescript-playground/#Curry_Optimization">advanced optimizations</a> for curried calling convention, however, the most efficient code is efficient code not relying on optimizations.</p>
<p>Since this release, we provide first class uncurried calling convention, <em>all toolchains provided by BuckleScript</em> can understand uncurried calling convention</p>
]]></summary>
        <author>
        </author>
    </entry>
